    <stitle>VT 275 Engine Diagnostics Manual - Performance Diagnostics - Test Procedures - 4. Engine Oil</stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc id="s305010603.4" svcproctype="diagnose" graphiccount="1">
        <title>4. Engine Oil</title>
        <figure id="f305010614" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figj31/J31095.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
            <caption></caption>
        </figure>
        <para id="tp305010604">
            <title>Purpose</title>To determine if crankcase oil level and oil quality are correct to ensure operation of
            the Injection Control Pressure (ICP) system
        </para>
        <randlist type="bullet">
            <title>Tools</title>
            <item>
                <para>None</para>
            </item>
        </randlist>
        <specpara>
            <warning>
                <para>To avoid personal injury, death, including damage to the engine or vehicle, read all safety
                    instructions in the "Safety Information" section of this manual.
                </para>
            </warning>
            <warning>
                <para>To avoid personal injury or death, do not allow engine fluids to stay on your skin. Clean skin and
                    nails with soap and water, or a good hand cleaner. Wash or properly dispose of clothing or rags
                    containing engine fluids. Engine fluids contain elements that may be unhealthy for skin and could
                    cause cancer.
                </para>
            </warning>
            <note>
                <para>Engine fluids, oil, fuel, and coolant, are a threat to the environment. Recycle or dispose of
                    engine fluids according to local regulations. Never dispose of engine fluids in the trash, on the
                    ground, in sewers, or in bodies of water.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Park vehicle on level ground.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Check oil level with oil level gauge.</para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Never check the oil level when the engine is running or immediately after engine shutdown; the
                        reading will be inaccurate. Allow 15 minute drain down time, before checking oil level.
                    </para>
                </note>
                <note>
                    <para>If the oil level is too low, the fuel injectors will not work correctly. If the oil level is
                        above the operating range, the engine has been incorrectly serviced, fuel is in the oil, or
                        coolant is in the oil.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Check oil for thickening and odor.</para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>Oil contaminated with long life coolant will cause thickening or coagulation.</para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Does oil have a diesel fuel odor?</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Check engine service records for correct oil grade and viscosity for ambient operating
                temperatures. See "Lubrication Requirements" in the Engine Operation and Maintenance Manual (for
                engine's model number and model year). Confirm that oil meets correct API category.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>Do not use 15W-40 oil below -7 &#176;C (20 &#176;F). Long oil drain intervals can increase oil
                        viscosity; thicker oil will make engine cranking and starting more difficult below freezing
                        temperatures.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
